Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{3} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop the chunks onto a
large (lined) #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then
toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Meanwhile, cut the @tomato{2} into small pieces.

Halve the @cucumber{1} lengthways, then slice into pieces.

Halve, peel and finely dice the @shallot{1}.

In a #bowl{}, toss the tomato, cucumber and shallot together with a drizzle of
oil and a pinch of salt and pepper.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Roughly chop the @parsley{5%g} (stalks and all).

Chop the @almonds{15%g}.

Pop the @breadcrumbs{1%pack} into a medium bowl along with the chopped parsley,
garlic and almonds.

Season with salt and stir everything together until you have an even mix.

> TIP: If you like, reserve a pinch of parsley for garnish.

Crack @egg{1} (double for 4p) into a deep #plate{} and carefully mix with a #fork{}.

Dip the @hake{250%g} in the egg to coat evenly.

Coat the hake in the almond breadcrumb mix.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Arrange the coated hake on a separate lined baking tray.

Lightly salt the fish and drizzle over a little oil.

Bake until the crumb is golden and the fish is cooked through, ~{10-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Serve the almond crusted hake with roast potatoes and salad alongside.

Sprinkle over any remaining parsley to finish.